# Reaction handling needs an intent classifier

## Decision (Joel, 2026-07-17)

Deterministic reaction→intent mapping is a dead end. Telegram exposes a
huge and open reaction set (the standard emoji set plus custom/premium
emoji), so you cannot enumerate a reaction→action table that survives
contact with how Joel actually reacts. "Deterministic processing is
no-joy."

The right model: an **intent classifier**. When Joel drops any reaction
on a signal/digest/action message, classify the reaction (+ the message
it's on, + light context) into an intent — acknowledge, dismiss, snooze,
approve, "good", "not now", etc. — rather than pattern-matching the
literal emoji. Whatever he taps, infer what he meant.

## Why this fits the system

- The Chat SDK already consumes reaction/reply events by `flowId`
  (see the `messaging` skill / chat-sdk work), so the plumbing to
  receive a reaction on a known message exists. The gap is
  interpretation, not transport.
- It mirrors the outbound side: we stopped keyword-scanning message
  content and started classifying by producer/intent. Inbound
  reactions deserve the same — classify intent, don't table-match.
- Buttons stay the precise path (explicit `act:` callbacks with
  receipts); reactions become the loose, forgiving path where the
  classifier maps a casual tap to the same underlying action.

## Build (when picked up)

- A small classifier (LLM via `pi`, not a paid key) that takes
  `{ reaction, messageText, flowId, availableIntents }` → an intent +
  confidence.
- Map the classified intent onto the existing action registry /
  `handleDigestActionCallback` path so a reaction and a button press
  converge on the same receipt-gated mutation.
- Low-confidence → do nothing (or a gentle "did you mean…"), never a
  wrong destructive action from a misread emoji.
- Non-actionable reactions (👍 on an FYI) are fine to just log.

## Non-goals

- No enumerated emoji→action table.
- Don't let a reaction trigger a `Done`-class source mutation without
  the same safety the button path has (readback, receipt).
